103
00:05:23,410 --> 00:05:24,498
He looked pretty good.

104
00:05:24,541 --> 00:05:25,368
Yeah, well, looks ain't

105
00:05:25,412 --> 00:05:26,935
everything.

106
00:05:26,978 --> 00:05:28,545
I guess.

107
00:05:30,242 --> 00:05:31,592
Would you mind?

108
00:05:31,635 --> 00:05:33,028
Give it here.

109
00:05:35,422 --> 00:05:36,814
Five for the #2 horse

110
00:05:36,858 --> 00:05:37,946
to win in the first.

111
00:05:37,989 --> 00:05:40,165
Five for the #4 in the second,

112
00:05:40,209 --> 00:05:42,516
but only if it's over 7/2.

113
00:05:42,559 --> 00:05:46,520
And... and...

114
00:05:48,478 --> 00:05:49,914
And?

115
00:05:49,958 --> 00:05:52,134
And ten for Manifest Wind

116
00:05:52,177 --> 00:05:54,310
in the seventh.

117
00:05:54,354 --> 00:05:56,399
A hunch bet?

118
00:05:56,443 --> 00:05:58,183
A hunch bet?

119
00:05:58,227 --> 00:05:59,228
[chuckles]

120
00:05:59,271 --> 00:06:01,143
I thought I taught you better.

121
00:06:01,186 --> 00:06:02,623
Sometimes I--

122
00:06:02,666 --> 00:06:03,667
Well, sometimes is never when

123
00:06:03,711 --> 00:06:05,103
you're betting without stats.

124
00:06:11,022 --> 00:06:12,676
It's your money.

125
00:06:14,199 --> 00:06:15,331
I'll pick the rest up

126
00:06:15,375 --> 00:06:16,201
after school.

127
00:06:16,245 --> 00:06:17,899
Thanks, Mooney.

128
00:06:19,988 --> 00:06:21,424
A hunch bet.

129
00:06:21,468 --> 00:06:22,817
Unbelievable.

130
00:06:24,384 --> 00:06:26,124
 The flag is up...

131
00:06:26,168 --> 00:06:27,169
[gate bell ringing]

132
00:06:27,212 --> 00:06:28,910
 ...and they're off!

133
00:06:28,953 --> 00:06:30,520
 Mud Dog in the lead,

134
00:06:30,564 --> 00:06:33,610
 followed by Wolf Creek.

135
00:06:33,654 --> 00:06:35,612
 Mud Dog and Wolf Creek continue

136
00:06:35,656 --> 00:06:36,744
 to battle for the lead.

137
00:06:36,787 --> 00:06:38,398
 Manifest Wind is just further

138
00:06:38,441 --> 00:06:39,877
 back, then Rambling Rocket.

139
00:06:39,921 --> 00:06:41,313
 Running on hydrosphere

140
00:06:41,357 --> 00:06:43,054
 are the field, and they've run

141
00:06:43,098 --> 00:06:44,621
 to the top of the turn.

142
00:06:44,665 --> 00:06:45,622
[crowd cheering]

143
00:06:45,666 --> 00:06:47,319
 The number two horse,

144
00:06:47,363 --> 00:06:49,844
 Manifest Wind, breaks away

145
00:06:49,887 --> 00:06:50,888
 from the pack,

146
00:06:50,932 --> 00:06:52,629
 down the final stretch

147
00:06:52,673 --> 00:06:54,501
 to take the lead.

148
00:06:54,544 --> 00:06:56,807
 Wolf Creek tries to stay

149
00:06:56,851 --> 00:06:58,809
 with him, but Manifest Wind

150
00:06:58,853 --> 00:07:00,463
 heads for the wire!

151
00:07:00,507 --> 00:07:03,466
 A length down lays the head

152
00:07:03,510 --> 00:07:06,426
 of Wolf Creek.

153
00:07:06,469 --> 00:07:07,992
 Manifest Wind's going to win

154
00:07:08,036 --> 00:07:09,472
 this race by a length.

155
00:07:09,516 --> 00:07:11,343
 Mud Dog and Wolf Creek

156
00:07:11,387 --> 00:07:12,867
 second and third.

157
00:07:12,910 --> 00:07:14,608
Manifest Wind, a fine young

158
00:07:14,651 --> 00:07:16,087
prospect from one of racing's

159
00:07:16,131 --> 00:07:17,611
best-known stables.

160
00:07:17,654 --> 00:07:18,960
 Now in the winner's circle

161
00:07:19,003 --> 00:07:20,962
 is Manifest Wind.

162
00:07:21,005 --> 00:07:22,746
Ha, a hunch bet.

163
00:07:22,790 --> 00:07:24,487
Who'd you have to win here?

164
00:07:25,662 --> 00:07:28,665
Who else? Manifest Wind.

165
00:07:28,709 --> 00:07:30,450
Don't you have all the luck?

166
00:07:30,493 --> 00:07:32,103
I know my horses, Eddie.

167
00:07:32,147 --> 00:07:33,148
Yeah, well, I'll go check

168
00:07:33,191 --> 00:07:34,323
on our horses and clean up.

169
00:07:34,366 --> 00:07:36,020
I'll meet you at home.

170
00:07:43,332 --> 00:07:44,812
Great race, Mrs. Slauson.

171
00:07:44,855 --> 00:07:46,204
Oh, why, thank you, dear.

172
00:07:46,248 --> 00:07:47,641
I had him to win, too.

173
00:07:47,684 --> 00:07:49,425
You did?

174
00:07:49,469 --> 00:07:50,339
He took the first pole

175
00:07:50,382 --> 00:07:51,296
like a champ.

176
00:07:51,340 --> 00:07:52,472
But didn't you think he slowed

177
00:07:52,515 --> 00:07:53,777
down in the last stretch?

178
00:07:53,821 --> 00:07:54,996
Harland, this young girl

179
00:07:55,039 --> 00:07:56,040
wants your job.

180
00:07:56,084 --> 00:07:56,954
Well, from the mouths

181
00:07:56,998 --> 00:07:58,086
of babes...

182
00:07:59,435 --> 00:08:01,350
You got lucky this time, kid.

183
00:08:01,393 --> 00:08:03,178
Mooney.

184
00:08:03,221 --> 00:08:05,180
Just remember, all hunch

185
00:08:05,223 --> 00:08:07,138
players die broke.

186
00:08:07,182 --> 00:08:08,966
I'll see you in the morning.

187
00:08:11,752 --> 00:08:13,188
Gotta be honest, Pop,

188
00:08:13,231 --> 00:08:14,537
this is not the season for

189
00:08:14,581 --> 00:08:15,625
two-year-olds.

190
00:08:15,669 --> 00:08:17,148
Eddie's having a tough time

191
00:08:17,192 --> 00:08:18,976
finding any to condition.

192
00:08:19,020 --> 00:08:20,325
All the big barns seem to be

193
00:08:20,369 --> 00:08:21,544
buying the promising youngsters

194
00:08:21,588 --> 00:08:23,111
at the auctions.

195
00:08:23,154 --> 00:08:25,983
We're trying our best.

196
00:08:26,027 --> 00:08:27,158
What can you do with just

197
00:08:27,202 --> 00:08:30,118
a couple of broken-down horses?

198
00:08:30,161 --> 00:08:31,772
I'm concentrating more on my

199
00:08:31,815 --> 00:08:33,817
handicapping...

200
00:08:33,861 --> 00:08:35,123
which I know you wouldn't

201
00:08:35,166 --> 00:08:37,299
approve of, Mama, but how else

202
00:08:37,342 --> 00:08:38,561
can we make ends meet?

203
00:08:38,605 --> 00:08:39,475
[door creaking]

204
00:08:39,519 --> 00:08:41,477
Hey Danny, loan me a 20, huh?

205
00:08:41,521 --> 00:08:43,131
Sorry, I don't got.

206
00:08:43,174 --> 00:08:45,176
I've seen your winnings.

207
00:08:45,220 --> 00:08:47,831
Empty, see?

208
00:08:47,875 --> 00:08:48,528
What about that one

209
00:08:48,571 --> 00:08:49,441
right there?

210
00:08:49,485 --> 00:08:51,095
Our savings, Eddie?

211
00:08:51,139 --> 00:08:52,706
Come on, just 'til tomorrow.

212
00:08:52,749 --> 00:08:53,881
Look, if we're ever going to

213
00:08:53,924 --> 00:08:55,012
get ahead, we have to follow

214
00:08:55,056 --> 00:08:55,926
our budget--

215
00:08:55,970 --> 00:08:57,319
Yeah, yeah, yeah, just give--

216
00:08:57,362 --> 00:08:59,060
Absolutely, positively not

217
00:08:59,103 --> 00:09:00,278
the savings.

218
00:09:00,322 --> 00:09:01,105
You know what your trouble

219
00:09:01,149 --> 00:09:01,976
is?

220
00:09:02,019 --> 00:09:03,804
You're too old for your age.

221
00:09:09,810 --> 00:09:11,289
Gonna be a late night.

222
00:09:11,333 --> 00:09:12,290
Nah, I got that meeting in

223
00:09:12,334 --> 00:09:14,118
the morning with Cornell Baynes.

224
00:09:14,162 --> 00:09:15,206
The big shot old Solly

225
00:09:15,250 --> 00:09:16,077
trains for?

226
00:09:16,120 --> 00:09:16,991
Yep.

227
00:09:17,034 --> 00:09:17,644
That's what he wanted

228
00:09:17,687 --> 00:09:18,340
to talk about?

229
00:09:18,383 --> 00:09:19,254
Yeah.

230
00:09:19,297 --> 00:09:20,560
And you're going out tonight?

231
00:09:20,603 --> 00:09:21,691
Just a couple of beers

232
00:09:21,735 --> 00:09:22,866
with the guys.

233
00:09:22,910 --> 00:09:24,128
Nothing doing.

234
00:09:24,172 --> 00:09:25,260
A meeting like that, you need

235
00:09:25,303 --> 00:09:26,609
a good night's rest.

236
00:09:26,653 --> 00:09:28,132
Hey, who's the adult here

237
00:09:28,176 --> 00:09:29,351
anyway?

238
00:09:36,488 --> 00:09:40,667
♪♪

239
00:10:16,616 --> 00:10:18,313
Don't you worry.

240
00:10:18,356 --> 00:10:20,837
Eddie and me, we're doing okay.

241
00:10:33,328 --> 00:10:35,591
Solly here tells me you've

242
00:10:35,635 --> 00:10:37,332
got the magic touch, Eddie.

243
00:10:37,375 --> 00:10:38,550
That so?

244
00:10:38,594 --> 00:10:40,683
I-- I don't know about magic.

245
00:10:40,727 --> 00:10:41,771
I admired your brother

246
00:10:41,815 --> 00:10:42,903
very much.

247
00:10:42,946 --> 00:10:44,252
One fine horseman.

248
00:10:44,295 --> 00:10:45,645
John was the best.

249
00:10:45,688 --> 00:10:47,211
He trained Wild Wonder,

250
00:10:47,255 --> 00:10:47,995
am I right?

251
00:10:48,038 --> 00:10:48,996
Yes, sir.

252
00:10:49,039 --> 00:10:50,519
Oh, what a horse.

253
00:10:50,562 --> 00:10:51,302
What a horse!

254
00:10:51,346 --> 00:10:52,173
He would've beat 'em all

255
00:10:52,216 --> 00:10:53,174
in the Tucker Stakes

256
00:10:53,217 --> 00:10:54,349
if he'd had the chance.

257
00:10:54,392 --> 00:10:55,567
Oh, terrible tragedy,

258
00:10:55,611 --> 00:10:56,612
that car wreck.

259
00:10:56,656 --> 00:10:57,657
John and Molly, they were

260
00:10:57,700 --> 00:10:58,788
good people.

261
00:10:58,832 --> 00:11:00,660
They had a little girl.

262
00:11:00,703 --> 00:11:02,313
Uh, Danny.

263
00:11:02,357 --> 00:11:03,663
Danielle.

264
00:11:06,535 --> 00:11:08,058
Well, to business.

265
00:11:08,102 --> 00:11:10,931
Eddie, I grabbed a little filly

266
00:11:10,974 --> 00:11:12,410
at auction last summer.

267
00:11:12,454 --> 00:11:14,238
Good price, good blood.

268
00:11:14,282 --> 00:11:15,544
Now, she don't do much

269
00:11:15,587 --> 00:11:16,240
in the morning.

270
00:11:16,284 --> 00:11:17,764
She's a real loafer.

271
00:11:17,807 --> 00:11:19,287
And Solly doesn't have time

272
00:11:19,330 --> 00:11:20,462
to mess with the horse,

273
00:11:20,505 --> 00:11:22,116
so we, uh, you know...

274
00:11:22,159 --> 00:11:23,465
We figure we're gonna take

275
00:11:23,508 --> 00:11:24,596
her out of state, run her in one

276
00:11:24,640 --> 00:11:25,467
of them little tracks,

277
00:11:25,510 --> 00:11:26,468
show she can win.

278
00:11:26,511 --> 00:11:28,035
Then bring her back in,

279
00:11:28,078 --> 00:11:30,080
sell her off real fast.

280
00:11:30,124 --> 00:11:32,082
I told Mr. Baynes Eddie

281
00:11:32,126 --> 00:11:33,562
Fortuna's the man for that job.

282
00:11:33,605 --> 00:11:35,303
Well, I'm-- I'm flattered.

283
00:11:35,346 --> 00:11:37,305
I told Mr. Baynes, "I don't

284
00:11:37,348 --> 00:11:39,350
know how he do it but he do it."

285
00:11:39,394 --> 00:11:41,483
[chuckling]

286
00:11:44,529 --> 00:11:46,009
This life is fit to kill

287
00:11:46,053 --> 00:11:47,750
a man.

288
00:11:47,794 --> 00:11:49,883
I've been rubbing horses so long

289
00:11:49,926 --> 00:11:51,188
I forget there's a world

290
00:11:51,232 --> 00:11:52,668
out there.

291
00:11:52,712 --> 00:11:53,582
Why don't you just get

292
00:11:53,625 --> 00:11:55,018
your trainer's license?

